   <text>
      <body>
         <head><title type="main" rend="center">An Elegiac Ballad.<emph rend="super">1</emph><note
                  type="head" place="bottom"><emph rend="super">1</emph> Published in <emph
                     rend="italic">Columbian Herald and New Daily Advertiser</emph> [Charleston, SC]
                  (April 15, 1796), p. 4.</note></title></head>
        
         <div1 type="stanza">
            <head rend="center">I.</head>
            <lg>
               <l>Where broad Fortha’s blue green billows<emph rend="super">2</emph><note
                  type="gloss" place="bottom"><emph rend="super">2</emph> The River Forth flows west to
                  east from the eastern slopes of Ben Lomond to the Firth of Forth and the
                  North Sea.</note></l>
               <l>Murmur to the azure main,</l>
               <l>Colin<emph rend="super">3</emph><note type="gloss" place="bottom"><emph
                        rend="super">3</emph> Shepherd-poet. Cf. Clement Marot’s <emph rend="italic"
                        >Complainte de Madame Loysc</emph> (1531); Edmund Spenser’s <emph
                        rend="italic">Shepheardes Calendar</emph> (1579) and John Gay’s <emph
                        rend="italic">The Shepherd’s Week</emph> (1714). </note> lay among the
                  willows,</l>
               <l>Colin, erst a happy swain,</l>
               <l n="5">When on Clyde’s sweet banks<emph rend="super">4</emph><note type="gloss"
                     place="bottom"><emph rend="super">4</emph> Rising in the Lanarkshire hills, the
                     river Clyde flows through Glasgow, eventually merging into the Firth of
                     Clyde.</note> he sported,</l>
               <l>Careless as the herds that graze,</l>
               <l>And the tuneful Muses courted</l>
               <l>To record his Peggy’s<emph rend="super">5</emph><note type="gloss" place="bottom"
                        ><emph rend="super">5</emph> Variant of Meggy, a diminutive of Margaret;
                     Peggy was the heroine of a popular sixteenth century ballad, “Bonny Peggy
                     Ramsey” or “Peg a Ramsey,” referenced in Shakespeare’s <emph
                        rend="italic">Twelfth Night</emph> (c.1601), II.iii.</note> praise. </l>
            </lg>
         </div1>
         <div1 type="stanza">
            <head rend="center">II.</head>
            <lg>
               <l>Now forsaken by the maiden,</l>
               <l n="10">Yet by restless love oppress’d,</l>
               <l>All with deepest sorrow laden,</l>
               <l>Thus the youth his pain express’d:</l>
               <l>“Summer glorious and resplendent,</l>
               <l>Wakes the early morn with glee,</l>
               <l n="15">Phoebus<emph rend="super">6</emph><note type="gloss" place="bottom"><emph
                        rend="super">6</emph> God of light, or the sun.</note> o’er you mountain
                  pendant</l>
               <l>Shines with joy on all but me!</l>
            </lg>
         </div1>

         <div1 type="stanza">
            <head rend="center">III.</head>
            <lg>
               <l>“Pleasures past with pain reviewing</l>
               <l>In tormenting prospect rise,</l>
               <l>Mem’ry love’s lost joys renewing</l>
               <l n="20">Opes the fountains of mine eyes;</l>
               <l>Hope, her syren song suspended,</l>
               <l>Smooths no more my brow of care:</l>
               <l>Rage with disappointment blended</l>
               <l>Pictures ruin and despair! </l>
            </lg>
         </div1>
         <div1 type="stanza">
            <head rend="center">IV.</head>
            <lg>
               <l n="25">“Welcome then, each gloomy dwelling,</l>
               <l>Horror’s desolate domains,</l>
               <l>Where, of human woes still telling,</l>
               <l>Tear ey’d Melancholy reigns!</l>
               <l>Fortha, roll thy blue green billows,</l>
               <l n="30">Murmur smoothly to the main!</l>
               <l>Wave ye sighing winds the willows,</l>
               <l>Help me riendly<emph rend="super">7</emph><note type="gloss" place="bottom"><emph
                        rend="super">7</emph> Printed as such in <emph rend="italic">Columbian
                        Herald and New Daily Advertiser</emph> [Charleston, SC] (April 15, 1796);
                     perhaps a misprint for “roundly.”</note> to complain!”</l>
            </lg>
         </div1>
      </body>
